[src:defunctionalization/currying] In mathematics and computer science, **currying** is the technique of translating a function that takes multiple arguments into a sequence of families of functions, each taking a single argument.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In this example, ${\mbox{curry}}$ itself becomes a function that takes f as an argument, and returns a function that maps each x to $f_{x}.$ The proper notation for expressing this is verbose.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] These definitions vary from context to context, and take different forms, depending on the theory that one is working in.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying is related to, but not the same as, partial application.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The example above can be used to illustrate partial application; it is quite similar.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The currying of a function with more than two arguments can be defined by induction.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying is useful in both practical and theoretical settings.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In functional programming languages, and many others, it provides a way of automatically managing how arguments are passed to functions and exceptions.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In theoretical computer science, it provides a way to study functions with multiple arguments in simpler theoretical models which provide only one argument.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The concept of currying was introduced by Gottlob Frege, developed by Moses Schönfinkel, and further developed by Haskell Curry.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying provides a way for working with functions that take multiple arguments, and using them in frameworks where functions might take only one argument.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] For example, some analytical techniques can only be applied to functions with a single argument.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Practical functions frequently take more arguments than this.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Frege showed that it was sufficient to provide solutions for the single argument case, as it was possible to transform a function with multiple arguments into a chain of single-argument functions instead.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] This transformation is the process now known as currying.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] All "ordinary" functions that might typically be encountered in mathematical analysis or in computer programming can be curried.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] However, there are categories in which currying is not possible; the most general categories which allow currying are the closed monoidal categories.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Some programming languages almost always use curried functions to achieve multiple arguments; notable examples are ML and Haskell, where in both cases all functions have exactly one argument.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] This property is inherited from lambda calculus, where multi-argument functions are usually represented in curried form.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying is related to, but not the same as partial application.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In practice, the programming technique of closures can be used to perform partial application and a kind of currying, by hiding arguments in an environment that travels with the curried function.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The "Curry" in "Currying" is a reference to logician Haskell Curry, who used the concept extensively, but Moses Schönfinkel had the idea six years before Curry.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The alternative name "Schönfinkelisation" has been proposed.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In the mathematical context, the principle can be traced back to work in 1893 by Frege.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The originator of the word "currying" is not clear.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Reynolds defined "currying" in a 1972 paper, but did not claim to have coined the term.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying is most easily understood by starting with an informal definition, which can then be molded to fit many different domains.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] First, there is some notation to be established.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The notation $X\to Y$ denotes all functions from X to Y .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] If f is such a function, we write $f\colon X\to Y$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Let $X\times Y$ denote the ordered pairs of the elements of X and Y respectively, that is, the Cartesian product of X and Y .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Here, X and Y may be sets, or they may be types, or they may be other kinds of objects, as explored below.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] That is, g takes an argument of type X and returns a function of type $Y\to Z$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In set theory, the notation $Y^{X}$ is used to denote the set of functions from the set X to the set Y .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying is the natural bijection between the set $A^{B\times C}$ of functions from $B\times C$ to A , and the set $(A^{C})^{B}$ of functions from B to the set of functions from C to A .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Indeed, it is this natural bijection that justifies the exponential notation for the set of functions.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] As is the case in all instances of currying, the formula above describes an adjoint pair of functors: for every fixed set C , the functor $B\mapsto B\times C$ is left adjoint to the functor $A\mapsto A^{C}$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In the category of sets, the object $Y^{X}$ is called the exponential object.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In the theory of function spaces, such as in functional analysis or homotopy theory, one is commonly interested in continuous functions between topological spaces.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] One writes ${\text{Hom}}(X,Y)$ (the Hom functor) for the set of *all* functions from X to Y , and uses the notation $Y^{X}$ to denote the subset of continuous functions.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] This is also the case when X , Y and $Y^{X}$ are compactly generated, although there are more cases.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] One useful corollary is that a function is continuous if and only if its curried form is continuous.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] is continuous when $Y^{X}$ is compact-open and Y locally compact Hausdorff.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] These two results are central for establishing the continuity of homotopy, i.e. when X is the unit interval I , so that $Z^{I\times Y}\cong (Z^{Y})^{I}$ can be thought of as either a homotopy of two functions from Y to Z , or, equivalently, a single (continuous) path in $Z^{Y}$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In algebraic topology, currying serves as an example of Eckmann–Hilton duality, and, as such, plays an important role in a variety of different settings.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] where $[A,B]$ is the set of homotopy classes of maps $A\rightarrow B$ , and $\Sigma A$ is the suspension of *A*, and $\Omega A$ is the loop space of *A*.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In essence, the suspension $\Sigma X$ can be seen as the cartesian product of X with the unit interval, modulo an equivalence relation to turn the interval into a loop.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The curried form then maps the space X to the space of functions from loops into Z , that is, from X into $\Omega Z$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Then ${\text{curry}}$ is the adjoint functor that maps suspensions to loop spaces, and uncurrying is the dual.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The duality between the mapping cone and the mapping fiber (cofibration and fibration) can be understood as a form of currying, which in turn leads to the duality of the long exact and coexact Puppe sequences.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In homological algebra, the relationship between currying and uncurrying is known as tensor-hom adjunction.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Here, an interesting twist arises: the Hom functor and the tensor product functor might not lift to an exact sequence; this leads to the definition of the Ext functor and the Tor functor.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In order theory, the theory of lattices of partially ordered sets, ${\text{curry}}$ is a continuous function when the lattice is given the Scott topology.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Scott-continuous functions were first investigated in the attempt to provide a semantics for lambda calculus (as ordinary set theory is inadequate to do this).
[src:defunctionalization/currying] More generally, Scott-continuous functions are now studied in domain theory, which encompasses the study of denotational semantics of computer algorithms.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Note that the Scott topology is quite different than many common topologies one might encounter in the category of topological spaces; the Scott topology is typically finer, and is not sober.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The notion of continuity makes its appearance in homotopy type theory, where, roughly speaking, two computer programs can be considered to be homotopic, i.e. compute the same results, if they can be "continuously" refactored from one to the other.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In theoretical computer science, currying provides a way to study functions with multiple arguments in very simple theoretical models, such as the lambda calculus, in which functions only take a single argument.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Consider a function $f(x,y)$ taking two arguments, and having the type $(X\times Y)\to Z$ , which should be understood to mean that *x* must have the type X , *y* must have the type Y , and the function itself returns the type Z .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] where $\lambda$ is the abstractor of lambda calculus.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The → operator is often considered right-associative, so the curried function type $X\to (Y\to Z)$ is often written as $X\to Y\to Z$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] That is, the parenthesis are not required to disambiguate the order of the application.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Curried functions may be used in any programming language that supports closures; however, uncurried functions are generally preferred for efficiency reasons, since the overhead of partial application and closure creation can then be avoided for most function calls.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In type theory, the general idea of a type system in computer science is formalized into a specific algebra of types.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] For example, when writing $f\colon X\to Y$ , the intent is that X and Y are types, while the arrow $\to$ is a type constructor, specifically, the function type or arrow type.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Similarly, the Cartesian product $X\times Y$ of types is constructed by the product type constructor $\times$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The type-theoretical approach is expressed in programming languages such as ML and the languages derived from and inspired by it: Caml, Haskell, and F#.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The type-theoretical approach provides a natural complement to the language of category theory, as discussed below.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] This is because categories, and specifically, monoidal categories, have an internal language, with simply typed lambda calculus being the most prominent example of such a language.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] It is important in this context, because it can be built from a single type constructor, the arrow type.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying then endows the language with a natural product type.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The correspondence between objects in categories and types then allows programming languages to be re-interpreted as logics (via Curry–Howard correspondence), and as other types of mathematical systems, as explored further, below.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The exponential object $Q^{P}$ in the category of Heyting algebras is normally written as material implication $P\to Q$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Distributive Heyting algebras are Boolean algebras, and the exponential object has the explicit form $\neg P\lor Q$ , thus making it clear that the exponential object really is material implication.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The above notions of currying and uncurrying find their most general, abstract statement in category theory.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying is a universal property of an exponential object, and gives rise to an adjunction in cartesian closed categories.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] That is, there is a natural isomorphism between the morphisms from a binary product $f\colon (X\times Y)\to Z$ and the morphisms to an exponential object $g\colon X\to Z^{Y}$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Here, *Hom* denotes the (external) Hom-functor of all morphisms in the category, while $B\Rightarrow C$ denotes the internal hom functor in the closed monoidal category.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] For the category of sets, the two are the same.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] When the product is the cartesian product, then the internal hom $B\Rightarrow C$ becomes the exponential object $C^{B}$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying can break down in one of two ways.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] One is if a category is not closed, and thus lacks an internal hom functor (possibly because there is more than one choice for such a functor).
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Another way is if it is not monoidal, and thus lacks a product (that is, lacks a way of writing down pairs of objects).
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Categories that do have both products and internal homs are exactly the closed monoidal categories.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The setting of cartesian closed categories is sufficient for the discussion of classical logic; the more general setting of closed monoidal categories is suitable for quantum computation.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The difference between these two is that the product for cartesian categories (such as the category of sets, complete partial orders or Heyting algebras) is just the Cartesian product; it is interpreted as an ordered pair of items (or a list).
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Simply typed lambda calculus is the internal language of cartesian closed categories; and it is for this reason that pairs and lists are the primary types in the type theory of LISP, Scheme and many functional programming languages.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] By contrast, the product for monoidal categories (such as Hilbert space and the vector spaces of functional analysis) is the tensor product.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The internal language of such categories is linear logic, a form of quantum logic; the corresponding type system is the linear type system.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Such categories are suitable for describing entangled quantum states, and, more generally, allow a vast generalization of the Curry–Howard correspondence to quantum mechanics, to cobordisms in algebraic topology, and to string theory.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The linear type system, and linear logic are useful for describing synchronization primitives, such as mutual exclusion locks, and the operation of vending machines.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Currying and partial function application are often conflated.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] One of the significant differences between the two is that a call to a partially applied function returns the result right away, not another function down the currying chain; this distinction can be illustrated clearly for functions whose arity is greater than two.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Given a function of type $f\colon (X\times Y\times Z)\to N$ , currying produces ${\text{curry}}(f)\colon X\to (Y\to (Z\to N))$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] That is, while an evaluation of the first function might be represented as $f(1,2,3)$ , evaluation of the curried function would be represented as $f_{\text{curried}}(1)(2)(3)$ , applying each argument in turn to a single-argument function returned by the previous invocation.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Note that after calling $f_{\text{curried}}(1)$ , we are left with a function that takes a single argument and returns another function, not a function that takes two arguments.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] In contrast, **partial function application** refers to the process of fixing a number of arguments to a function, producing another function of smaller arity.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Given the definition of f above, we might fix (or 'bind') the first argument, producing a function of type ${\text{partial}}(f)\colon (Y\times Z)\to N$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Evaluation of this function might be represented as $f_{\text{partial}}(2,3)$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Note that the result of partial function application in this case is a function that takes two arguments.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Intuitively, partial function application says "if you fix the first argument of the function, you get a function of the remaining arguments".
[src:defunctionalization/currying] For example, if function *div* stands for the division operation *x*/*y*, then *div* with the parameter *x* fixed at 1 (i.e., *div* 1) is another function: the same as the function *inv* that returns the multiplicative inverse of its argument, defined by *inv*(*y*) = 1/*y*.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] The practical motivation for partial application is that very often the functions obtained by supplying some but not all of the arguments to a function are useful; for example, many languages have a function or operator similar to `plus_one`.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Partial application makes it easy to define these functions, for example by creating a function that represents the addition operator with 1 bound as its first argument.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Thus, partial application is reduced to a curried function at a fixed point.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Further, a curried function at a fixed point is (trivially), a partial application.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] For further evidence, note that, given any function $f(x,y)$ , a function $g(y,x)$ may be defined such that $g(y,x)=f(x,y)$ .
[src:defunctionalization/currying] Thus, any partial application may be reduced to a single curry operation.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] As such, curry is more suitably defined as an operation which, in many theoretical cases, is often applied recursively, but which is theoretically indistinguishable (when considered as an operation) from a partial application.
[src:defunctionalization/currying] So, a partial application can be defined as the objective result of a single application of the curry operator on some ordering of the inputs of some function.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] In programming languages, **defunctionalization** is a compile-time transformation which eliminates higher-order functions, replacing them by a single first-order *apply* function.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] The technique was first described by John C.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Reynolds in his 1972 paper, "Definitional Interpreters for Higher-Order Programming Languages".
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Reynolds' observation was that a given program contains only finitely many function abstractions, so that each can be assigned and replaced by a unique identifier.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Every function application within the program is then replaced by a call to the *apply* function with the function identifier as the first argument.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] The *apply* function's only job is to dispatch on this first argument, and then perform the instructions denoted by the function identifier on the remaining arguments.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] One complication to this basic idea is that function abstractions may reference free variables.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] In such situations, defunctionalization must be preceded by lambda lifting, so that any free variables of a function abstraction are passed as extra arguments to *apply*.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] In addition, if closures are supported as first-class values, it becomes necessary to represent these captured bindings by creating data structures.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Alternatively, the target language may support indirect calls through function pointers, which may be more efficient and extensible than a dispatch-based approach.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Besides its use as a compilation technique for higher-order functional languages, defunctionalization has been studied (particularly by Olivier Danvy and collaborators) as a way of mechanically transforming interpreters into abstract machines.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Defunctionalization is also related to the technique from object-oriented programming of representing functions by function objects (as an alternative to closures).
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] The following is a Haskell translation of an example due to Olivier Danvy.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Consider the `Tree` datatype and the following program.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Defunctionalization replaces all higher-order functions (in this case, `o` is the only higher-order function) with a value of the `Lam` datatype.
[src:defunctionalization/defunctionalization] Instead of calling higher-order functions directly, it introduces an `apply` function that interprets the `Lam` datatype.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In computer science, a programming language is said to have **first-class functions** if it treats functions as first-class citizens.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] This means the language supports passing functions as arguments to other functions, returning them as the values from other functions, and assigning them to variables or storing them in data structures.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Some programming language theorists require support for anonymous functions (function literals) as well.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In languages with first-class functions, the names of functions do not have any special status; they are treated like ordinary variables with a function type.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The term was coined by Christopher Strachey in the context of "functions as first-class citizens" in the mid-1960s.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] First-class functions are a necessity for the functional programming style, in which the use of higher-order functions is a standard practice.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] A simple example of a higher-ordered function is the *map* function, which takes, as its arguments, a function and a list, and returns the list formed by applying the function to each member of the list.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] For a language to support *map*, it must support passing a function as an argument.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] There are certain implementation difficulties in passing functions as arguments or returning them as results, especially in the presence of non-local variables introduced in nested and anonymous functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Historically, these were termed the *funarg problems*, the name coming from *function argument*.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In early imperative languages these problems were avoided by either not supporting functions as result types (e.g.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] ALGOL 60, Pascal) or omitting nested functions and thus non-local variables (e.g.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The early functional language Lisp took the approach of dynamic scoping, where non-local variables refer to the closest definition of that variable at the point where the function is executed, instead of where it was defined.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Proper support for lexically scoped first-class functions was introduced in Scheme and requires handling references to functions as closures instead of bare function pointers, which in turn makes garbage collection a necessity.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In this section, we compare how particular programming idioms are handled in a functional language with first-class functions (Haskell) compared to an imperative language where functions are second-class citizens (C).
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In languages where functions are first-class citizens, functions can be passed as arguments to other functions in the same way as other values (a function taking another function as argument is called a higher-order function).
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Languages where functions are not first-class often still allow one to write higher-order functions through the use of features such as function pointers or delegates.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] There are a number of differences between the two approaches that are *not* directly related to the support of first-class functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The Haskell sample operates on lists, while the C sample operates on arrays.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Both are the most natural compound data structures in the respective languages and making the C sample operate on linked lists would have made it unnecessarily complex.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Again, this is the most natural way to express this function in both languages, but the Haskell sample could easily have been expressed in terms of a fold and the C sample in terms of recursion.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Finally, the Haskell function has a polymorphic type, as this is not supported by C we have fixed all type variables to the type constant `int`.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] If functions are represented with bare function pointers, we can not know anymore how the value that is outside of the function's body should be passed to it, and because of that a closure needs to be built manually.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Therefore we can not speak of "first-class" functions here.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Also note that the `map` is now specialized to functions referring to two `int`s outside of their environment.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] This can be set up more generally, but requires more boilerplate code.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] If `f` would have been a nested function we would still have run into the same problem and this is the reason they are not supported in C.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] When returning a function, we are in fact returning its closure.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In the C example any local variables captured by the closure will go out of scope once we return from the function that builds the closure.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Forcing the closure at a later point will result in undefined behaviour, possibly corrupting the stack.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] This is known as the upwards funarg problem.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Assigning functions to variables and storing them inside (global) data structures potentially suffers from the same difficulties as returning functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] As one can test most literals and values for equality, it is natural to ask whether a programming language can support testing functions for equality.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] in general and even for functions with finite domains often intractable.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] For this reason no programming language implements function equality as extensional equality.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] are considered equal if they have the same "internal structure".
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Given the impracticality of implementing extensional and intensional equality, most languages supporting testing functions for equality use reference equality.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] All functions or closures are assigned a unique identifier (usually the address of the function body or the closure) and equality is decided based on equality of the identifier.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Two separately defined, but otherwise identical function definitions will be considered unequal.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Referential equality implies intensional and extensional equality.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In type theory, the type of functions accepting values of type *A* and returning values of type *B* may be written as *A* → *B* or *B**A*.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In the Curry–Howard correspondence, function types are related to logical implication; lambda abstraction corresponds to discharging hypothetical assumptions and function application corresponds to the modus ponens inference rule.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Besides the usual case of programming functions, type theory also uses first-class functions to model associative arrays and similar data structures.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] In category-theoretical accounts of programming, the availability of first-class functions corresponds to the closed category assumption.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] For instance, the simply typed lambda calculus corresponds to the internal language of Cartesian closed categories.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Functional programming languages, such as Erlang, Scheme, ML, Haskell, F#, and Scala, all have first-class functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] When Lisp, one of the earliest functional languages, was designed, not all aspects of first-class functions were then properly understood, resulting in functions being dynamically scoped.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The later Scheme and Common Lisp dialects do have lexically scoped first-class functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Many scripting languages, including Perl, Python, PHP, Lua, Tcl/Tk, JavaScript and Io, have first-class functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] For imperative languages, a distinction has to be made between Algol and its descendants such as Pascal, the traditional C family, and the modern garbage-collected variants.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The Algol family has allowed nested functions and higher-order taking function as arguments, but not higher-order functions that return functions as results (except Algol 68, which allows this).
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The reason for this was that it was not known how to deal with non-local variables if a nested-function was returned as a result (and Algol 68 produces runtime errors in such cases).
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The C family allowed both passing functions as arguments and returning them as results, but avoided any problems by not supporting nested functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] (The gcc compiler allows them as an extension.) As the usefulness of returning functions primarily lies in the ability to return nested functions that have captured non-local variables, instead of top-level functions, these languages are generally not considered to have first-class functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Modern imperative languages often support garbage-collection making the implementation of first-class functions feasible.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] First-class functions have often only been supported in later revisions of the language, including C# 2.0 and Apple's Blocks extension to C, C++, and Objective-C.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] C++11 has added support for anonymous functions and closures to the language, but because of the non-garbage collected nature of the language, special care has to be taken for non-local variables in functions to be returned as results (see below).
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Explicit partial application possible with `std::bind`.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Partial application possible with user-land code.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Partial application possible by automatic generation of new functions.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Partial application possible through library.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] (the variable lives as long as the closure does).
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The first option is safe if the closure is returned but requires a copy and cannot be used to modify the original variable (which might not exist any more at the time the closure is called).
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The third option is safe if the closure is returned and does not require a copy but cannot be used to modify the original variable either.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] closures can only capture final or "effectively final" non-local variables.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Anonymous functions take the type inferred from the context.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] variants do not support closures or need a special construct to create closures.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] , the identifier of a function in the function namespace cannot be used as a reference to a first-class value.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The identifier of a regular "function" in Ruby (which is really a method) cannot be used as a value or passed.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] The syntax for calling such a function object differs from calling regular methods.
[src:defunctionalization/first-class-function] Nested method definitions do not actually nest the scope.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] All other functions are *first-order functions*.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] In mathematics higher-order functions are also termed *operators* or *functionals*.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] The differential operator in calculus is a common example, since it maps a function to its derivative, also a function.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Higher-order functions should not be confused with other uses of the word "functor" throughout mathematics, see Functor (disambiguation).
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] In the untyped lambda calculus, all functions are higher-order; in a typed lambda calculus, from which most functional programming languages are derived, higher-order functions that take one function as argument are values with types of the form $(\tau _{1}\to \tau _{2})\to \tau _{3}$ .
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] In the following examples, the higher-order function `twice` takes a function, and applies the function to some value twice.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] If `twice` has to be applied several times for the same `f` it preferably should return a function rather than a value.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] This is in line with the "don't repeat yourself" principle.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Alternatively, we can also compose using pure anonymous functions.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] In this Erlang example, the higher-order function `or_else/2` takes a list of functions (`Fs`) and argument (`X`).
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] It evaluates the function `F` with the argument `X` as argument.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns false then the next function in `Fs` will be evaluated.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns `{false, Y}` then the next function in `Fs` with argument `Y` will be evaluated.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns `R` the higher-order function `or_else/2` will return `R`.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Note that `X`, `Y`, and `R` can be functions.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Notice a function literal can be defined either with an identifier (`twice`) or anonymously (assigned to variable `plusThree`).
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Note that arrow functions implicitly capture any variables that come from the parent scope, whereas anonymous functions require the `use` keyword to do the same.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Python decorator syntax is often used to replace a function with the result of passing that function through a higher-order function.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] In Raku, all code objects are closures and therefore can reference inner "lexical" variables from an outer scope because the lexical variable is "closed" inside of the function.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Raku also supports "pointy block" syntax for lambda expressions which can be assigned to a variable or invoked anonymously.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Tcl uses apply command to apply an anonymous function (since 8.6).
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] The XACML standard defines higher-order functions in the standard to apply a function to multiple values of attribute bags.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] The list of higher-order functions in XACML can be found here.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Function pointers in languages such as C, C++, Fortran, and Pascal allow programmers to pass around references to functions.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] The qsort function from the C standard library uses a function pointer to emulate the behavior of a higher-order function.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Macros can also be used to achieve some of the effects of higher-order functions.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] However, macros cannot easily avoid the problem of variable capture; they may also result in large amounts of duplicated code, which can be more difficult for a compiler to optimize.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Macros are generally not strongly typed, although they may produce strongly typed code.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] In other imperative programming languages, it is possible to achieve some of the same algorithmic results as are obtained via higher-order functions by dynamically executing code (sometimes called *Eval* or *Execute* operations) in the scope of evaluation.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] In object-oriented programming languages that do not support higher-order functions, objects can be an effective substitute.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] An object's methods act in essence like functions, and a method may accept objects as parameters and produce objects as return values.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Objects often carry added run-time overhead compared to pure functions, however, and added boilerplate code for defining and instantiating an object and its method(s).
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] Languages that permit stack-based (versus heap-based) objects or structs can provide more flexibility with this method.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] The function `a()` takes a `Txy` record as input and returns the integer value of the sum of the record's `x` and `y` fields (3 + 7).
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] In this case, different types are used to trigger different functions via function overloading.
[src:defunctionalization/higher-order-function] The overloaded function in this example has the signature `auto apply`.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The term "lambda lifting" was first introduced by Thomas Johnsson around 1982 and was historically considered as a mechanism for implementing programming languages based on functional programming.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] It is used in conjunction with other techniques in some modern compilers.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda lifting is not the same as closure conversion.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] It requires all call sites to be adjusted (adding extra arguments (parameters) to calls) and does not introduce a closure for the lifted lambda expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] In contrast, closure conversion does not require call sites to be adjusted but does introduce a closure for the lambda expression mapping free variables to values.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The technique may be used on individual functions, in code refactoring, to make a function usable outside the scope in which it was written.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda lifts may also be repeated, to transform the program.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Repeated lifts may be used to convert a program written in lambda calculus into a set of recursive functions, without lambdas.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] This demonstrates the equivalence of programs written in lambda calculus and programs written as functions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda lifting is expensive on processing time for the compiler.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] An efficient implementation of lambda lifting is $O(n^{2})$ on processing time for the compiler.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] In the untyped lambda calculus, where the basic types are functions, lifting may change the result of beta reduction of a lambda expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The resulting functions will have the same meaning, in a mathematical sense, but are not regarded as the same function in the untyped lambda calculus.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] See also intensional versus extensional equality.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The reverse operation to lambda lifting is lambda dropping.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda dropping may make the compilation of programs quicker for the compiler, and may also increase the efficiency of the resulting program, by reducing the number of parameters, and reducing the size of stack frames.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] However it makes a function harder to re-use.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] A dropped function is tied to its context, and can only be used in a different context if it is first lifted.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Replace each free variable with an additional argument to the enclosing function, and pass that argument to every use of the function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Replace every local function definition that has no free variables with an identical global function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Repeat steps 2 and 3 until all free variables and local functions are eliminated.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] If the language has closures as first-class objects that can be passed as arguments or returned from other functions, the closure will need to be represented by a data structure that captures the bindings of the free variables.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] (The `let rec` declares `sum` as a function that may call itself.) The function f, which adds sum's argument to the sum of the numbers less than the argument, is a local function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Within the definition of f, n is a free variable.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda lifting and closure are both methods for implementing block structured programs.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] It implements block structure by eliminating it.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] All functions are lifted to the global level.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Closure conversion provides a "closure" which links the current frame to other frames.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Closure conversion takes less compile time.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Recursive functions, and block structured programs, with or without lifting, may be implemented using a stack based implementation, which is simple and efficient.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] However a stack frame based implementation must be strict (eager).
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The stack frame based implementation requires that the life of functions be last-in, first-out (LIFO).
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] That is, the most recent function to start its calculation must be the first to end.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Some functional languages (such as Haskell) are implemented using lazy evaluation, which delays calculation until the value is needed.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The lazy implementation strategy gives flexibility to the programmer.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lazy evaluation requires delaying the call to a function until a request is made to the value calculated by the function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] One implementation is to record a reference to a "frame" of data describing the calculation, in place of the value.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Later when the value is required, the frame is used to calculate the value, just in time for when it is needed.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The calculated value then replaces the reference.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The "frame" is similar to a stack frame, the difference being that it is not stored on the stack.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lazy evaluation requires that all the data required for the calculation be saved in the frame.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] If the function is "lifted", then the frame needs only record the function pointer, and the parameters to the function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Some modern languages use garbage collection in place of stack based allocation to manage the life of variables.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] In a managed, garbage collected environment, a closure records references to the frames from which values may be obtained.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] In contrast a lifted function has parameters for each value needed in the calculation.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The Let expression is useful in describing lifting, dropping, and the relationship between recursive equations and lambda expressions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Most functional languages have let expressions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Also, block-structured programming languages like ALGOL and Pascal are similar in that they too allow the local definition of a function for use in a restricted scope.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The *let* expression used here is a fully mutually recursive version of *let rec*, as implemented in many functional languages.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Let expressions are related to Lambda calculus.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda calculus has a simple syntax and semantics, and is good for describing Lambda lifting.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] It is convenient to describe lambda lifting as a translations from *lambda* to a *let* expression, and lambda dropping as the reverse.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] This is because *let* expressions allow mutual recursion, which is, in a sense, more lifted than is supported in lambda calculus.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda calculus does not support mutual recursion and only one function may be defined at the outermost global scope.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Conversion rules which describe translation without lifting are given in the Let expression article.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Meta-functions will be given that describe lambda lifting and dropping.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] A meta-function is a function that takes a program as a parameter.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The program is data for the meta-program.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The program and the meta program are at different meta-levels.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] For simplicity the first rule given that matches will be applied.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The rules also assume that the lambda expressions have been pre-processed so that each lambda abstraction has a unique name.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The substitution operator is used extensively.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The expression $L[G:=S]$ means substitute every occurrence of *G* in *L* by *S* and return the expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The definition used is extended to cover the substitution of expressions, from the definition given on the Lambda calculus page.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The matching of expressions should compare expressions for alpha equivalence (renaming of variables).
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Each lambda lift takes a lambda abstraction which is a sub expression of a lambda expression and replaces it by a function call (application) to a function that it creates.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The free variables in the sub expression are the parameters to the function call.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda lifts may be used on individual functions, in code refactoring, to make a function usable outside the scope in which it was written.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Such lifts may also be repeated, until the expression has no lambda abstractions, to transform the program.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] A lift is given a sub-expression within an expression to lift to the top of that expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The expression may be part of a larger program.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] This allows control of where the sub-expression is lifted to.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The sub expression may be either a lambda abstraction, or a lambda abstraction applied to a parameter.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] An anonymous lift has a lift expression which is a lambda abstraction only.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] It is regarded as defining an anonymous function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] A name must be created for the function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] A named lift expression has a lambda abstraction applied to an expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] This lift is regarded as a named definition of a function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] An anonymous lift takes a lambda abstraction (called *S*).
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The lambda lift is the substitution of the lambda abstraction *S* for a function application, along with the addition of a definition for the function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The new lambda expression has *S* substituted for G: *L*[*S*:=*G*] means substitution of *S* for *G* in *L*.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The function definitions has the function definition *G = S* added.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] In the above rule *G* is the function application that is substituted for the expression *S*.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] where $\operatorname {vars} [E]$ is a meta function that returns the set of variables used in *E*.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The named lift is similar to the anonymous lift except that the function name *V* is provided.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] As for the anonymous lift, the expression *G* is constructed from *V* by applying the free variables of *S*.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] A lambda lift transformation takes a lambda expression and lifts all lambda abstractions to the top of the expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The abstractions are then translated into recursive functions, which eliminates the lambda abstractions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] where *M* is a series of function definitions, and *N* is the expression representing the value returned.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The *de-let* meta function may then be used to convert the result back into lambda calculus.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The processing of transforming the lambda expression is a series of lifts.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] After the lifts are applied the lets are combined together into a single let.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Then Parameter dropping is applied to remove parameters that are not necessary in the "let" expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The let expression allows the function definitions to refer to each other directly, whereas lambda abstractions are strictly hierarchical, and a function may not directly refer to itself.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] There are two different ways that an expression may be selected for lifting.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The first treats all lambda abstractions as defining anonymous functions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The second, treats lambda abstractions which are applied to a parameter as defining a function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Lambda abstractions applied to a parameter have a dual interpretation as either a let expression defining a function, or as defining an anonymous function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] These two predicates are needed for both definitions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Search for the deepest anonymous abstraction, so that when the lift is applied the function lifted will become a simple equation.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] This definition does not recognize a lambda abstractions with a parameter as defining a function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] All lambda abstractions are regarded as defining anonymous functions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Search for the deepest named or anonymous function definition, so that when the lift is applied the function lifted will become a simple equation.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] This definition recognizes a lambda abstraction with an actual parameter as defining a function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Only lambda abstractions without an application are treated as anonymous functions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] where M is lambda free and N is lambda free or an anonymous function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The first sub expression to be chosen for lifting is $\lambda x.f\ (x\ x)$ .
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] This transforms the lambda expression into $\lambda f.(p\ f)\ (p\ f)$ and creates the equation $p\ f\ x=f(x\ x)$ .
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The second sub expression to be chosen for lifting is $\lambda f.(p\ f)\ (p\ f)$ .
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] This transforms the lambda expression into $q\ p$ and creates the equation $q\ p\ f=(p\ f)\ (p\ f)$ .
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] Surprisingly this result is simpler than the one obtained from lifting named functions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The Y-Combinator calls its parameter (function) repeatedly on itself.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p01] The value is defined if the function has a fixed point.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] Lambda dropping is making the scope of functions smaller and using the context from the reduced scope to reduce the number of parameters to functions.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] Reducing the number of parameters makes functions easier to comprehend.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] In the Lambda lifting section, a meta function for first lifting and then converting the resulting lambda expression into recursive equation was described.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] The Lambda Drop meta function performs the reverse by first converting recursive equations to lambda abstractions, and then dropping the resulting lambda expression, into the smallest scope which covers all references to the lambda abstraction.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] A Lambda drop is applied to an expression which is part of a program.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] Dropping is controlled by a set of expressions from which the drop will be excluded.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] is the lambda abstraction to be dropped.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] is a set of expressions to be excluded from dropping.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] The lambda drop transformation sinks all abstractions in an expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] is a set of sub expressions to be excluded from the dropping.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] Sinking is moving a lambda abstraction inwards as far as possible such that it is still outside all references to the variable.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] Parameter dropping is optimizing a function for its position in the function.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] Lambda lifting added parameters that were necessary so that a function can be moved out of its context.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] In dropping, this process is reversed, and extra parameters that contain variables that are free may be removed.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] Dropping a parameter is removing an unnecessary parameter from a function, where the actual parameter being passed in is always the same expression.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] The free variables of the expression must also be free where the function is defined.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] In this case the parameter that is dropped is replaced by the expression in the body of the function definition.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] In this example the actual parameter for the formal parameter *o* is always *p*.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] As *p* is a free variable in the whole expression, the parameter may be dropped.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] The actual parameter for the formal parameter *y* is always *n*.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] However *n* is bound in a lambda abstraction.
[src:defunctionalization/lambda-lifting-p02] For each abstraction that defines a function, build the information required to make decisions on dropping names.
